1. Pixels (px)
# CSS
.box {
    width: 300px;
    height: 150px;
}
- Fixed size
- Does not scale automatically with parent size
- Good for borders, icons, and small UI elements

## Example
# HTML 
<div class="box"></div>

# CSS
.box {
    width: 200px;
    height: 100px;
    background: blue;
}

# 2. Percentage (%) - Relative to the parent element
# HTML
<div class="parent">
    <div class="child"></div>
</div>

# CSS
.parent {
    width: 600px;
}
.child {
    width: 50%;
}

# Calculation: 50% of 600px = 300px
Useful for:
- Responsive layouts
- Widths
- Heights (when the parent has a defined height)

# 3. em - Relative to the parent's font size
# CSS
.parent {
    font-size: 20px;
}

.child {
    font-size: 2em;
}
Result: 2 × 20px = 40px

# Nested elements can compound:
# CSS
.parent {
    font-size: 20px;
}
.child {
    font-size: 2em;
}
.grandchild {
    font-size: 2em;
}

Parent = 20px
Child = 40px
Grandchild = 80px
-> This compounding is why em requires careful use

1. Universal Selector (*)
Selects every element on the page

# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<p>Paragraph</p>
<button>Click Me</button>
# CSS
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
}
-> Used in almost every professional project as a CSS reset

2. Element (Tag) Selector - Targets every occurrence of a specific HTML tag
# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<h1>Another Heading</h1>
<p>Paragraph</p>
# CSS
h1 {
    color: red;
}

p {
    color: green;
}
3. Class Selector (.) - One of the most commonly used selectors
# HTML
<h1 class="title">Welcome</h1>
<h2 class="title">Frontend</h2>
# CSS
.title {
    color: blue;
}
-> Both elements are styled

4. ID Selector (#) - Targets a single unique element
# HTML
<h1 id="main-title">
    Welcome
</h1>
# CSS
#main-title {
    color: purple;
}

-> IDs should generally be unique within a page.

5. Multiple Classes
# HTML
<button class="btn primary">
    Login
</button>
# CSS
.btn {
    padding: 10px;
}

.primary {
    background: blue;
} -> The button gets styles from both classes

6. Group Selector (,) - Apply the same styles to multiple selectors
# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<h2>Heading 2</h2>
<p>Paragraph</p>
# CSS
h1,
h2,
p {
    color: green;
}
7. Descendant Selector (space) - Targets elements inside another element at any depth
# HTML
<div>
    <p>Hello</p>
</div>
# CSS
div p {
    color: blue;
} -> Works even if the <p> is nested several levels deep

8. Child Selector (>) - Targets only direct children
# HTML
<div>
    <p>Direct Child</p>
    <section>
        <p>Nested Child</p>
    </section>
</div>
# CSS
div > p {
    color: red;
} -> Only the first <p> is selected

9. Adjacent Sibling Selector (+) - Targets the immediate next sibling
# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<p>Paragraph</p>
<p>Another Paragraph</p>
# CSS
h1 + p {
    color: blue;
}
-> Only the first paragraph is selected

10. General Sibling Selector (~) - Targets all following siblings

# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<p>One</p>
<p>Two</p>
<p>Three</p>
# CSS
h1 ~ p {
    color: green;
} -> All paragraphs after the <h1> are selected

11. Attribute Selector
# HTML
<input type="text">
<input type="password">

# CSS
input[type="text"] {
    border: 2px solid blue;
}
12. Attribute Contains
# HTML
<a href="https://google.com">
Google
</a>
# CSS
a[href*="google"] {
    color: red;
}
*= means "contains"

13. Attribute Starts With (^=)
a[href^="https"] {
    color: green;
}

# Matches values that start with https

14. Attribute Ends With ($=)
img[src$=".png"] {
    border: 2px solid red;
} -> Matches values ending in .png

15. First Child
# HTML
<ul>
<li>HTML</li>
<li>CSS</li>
<li>JavaScript</li>
</ul>
# CSS
li:first-child {
    color: red;
}

16. Last Child
li:last-child {
    color: blue;
}

17. nth-child()
li:nth-child(2) {
    color: green;
} -> Selects the second child

Even items: li:nth-child(even)

Odd items: li:nth-child(odd)

# Every third item:
li:nth-child(3n)
18. nth-of-type()
p:nth-of-type(2) {
    color: orange;
}

-> Counts only <p> elements, ignoring other tag types.

19. Not Selector (:not)
<p class="active">One</p>

<p>Two</p>
Give feedback
p:not(.active) {
    color: gray;
}
20. Empty Selector
<div></div>

<div>Hello</div>
Give feedback
div:empty {
    border: 1px solid red;
}
21. Hover
button:hover {
    background: blue;
    color: white;
}
22. Focus
input:focus {
    border: 2px solid blue;
}
23. Active
button:active {
    transform: scale(0.95);
}
24. Checked
<input type="checkbox" checked>
Give feedback
input:checked {
    width: 30px;
}
25. Disabled
input:disabled {
    background: lightgray;
}
26. Enabled
input:enabled {
