    background: yellow;
    color: red;
}
36. Placeholder
input::placeholder {
    color: gray;
}
Selector Specificity (Very Important)

When multiple selectors target the same element, CSS uses specificity to decide which rule wins.

Selector	Specificity
Universal (*)	0
Element (h1)	1
Class (.title)	10
Attribute ([type="text"])	10
Pseudo-class (:hover)	10
ID (#header)	100
Inline style	1000
!important	Overrides normal specificity (use sparingly)

Example:

<h1 id="main" class="title">
    Hello
</h1>
Give feedback
h1 {
    color: red;
}

.title {
    color: blue;
}

#main {
    color: green;
}

The text will be green because the ID selector has the highest specificity among these rules.

Professional Selector Cheat Sheet
Selector	Example	Purpose
Universal	*	All elements
Element	h1	Tag selector
Class	.card	Reusable styles
ID	#header	Unique element
Group	h1, p	Multiple selectors
Descendant	div p	Any nested descendant
Child	div > p	Direct child only
Adjacent sibling	h1 + p	Immediate next sibling
General sibling	h1 ~ p	All following siblings
Attribute	input[type="text"]	Match attributes
Pseudo-class	button:hover	Element state
Pseudo-element	p::before	Part of an element
