4. rem - Relative to the root (html) font size
html {
    font-size: 16px;
}

h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
}

Result: 2 × 16px = 32px
# Unlike em, rem is not affected by nesting

# Most developers use:
- rem for font sizes
- rem for spacing
- rem for padding and margins

# 5. Viewport Width (vw) - Relative to the browser width
1vw = 1% of viewport width
.hero {
    width: 50vw;
}

If the browser is 1200px wide: 50vw = 600px
Useful for:
- Hero sections
- Responsive typography
- Full-width layouts

# 6. Viewport Height (vh) - Relative to the browser height
# 1vh = 1% of viewport height
.hero {
    height: 100vh;
}

-> The section fills the entire visible screen

7. vmin - Uses the smaller of the viewport width or height
# Example:
Viewport:
Width = 1200px
Height = 800px

1vmin = 8px

-> Useful for elements that should scale based on the smaller screen dimension

8. vmaxv- Uses the larger viewport dimension

Example:
Viewport:
Width = 1200px

Height = 800px

1vmax = 12px

9. ch - Based on the width of the "0" character

input {
    width: 30ch;
}

Useful for:
- Forms
- Text inputs
- Code editors

# 10. ex - Based on the height of the lowercase "x"
font-size: 3ex;
# Rarely used in modern web development

11. fr (Fraction) - Used only with CSS Grid
.container {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 2fr 1fr;
}

Layout:
|-----|----------|-----|
   1fr     2fr      1fr

# The middle column is twice as wide as the others

12. Auto - Allows the browser to calculate the value
.container {
    margin: auto;
} -> A common way to center block elements

13. fit-content - Element grows only as much as its content needs
button {
    width: fit-content;
}

14. min-content - Shrinks to the smallest width that still fits the content
width: min-content;
# Mostly used with CSS Grid and Flexbox

15. max-content - Expands to fit the content without wrapping
width: max-content;

